The paper deals with the Fourier Entropy-Influence conjecture, which is a fundamental problem in the study of Boolean functions. The paper uses techniques from computational complexity theory, information theory, and discrete mathematics to prove a composition theorem for the conjecture. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also deals with read-once formulas and decision trees, which are topics in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also uses Fourier analysis, which is a topic in cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper deals with the largest known ratio of $C$ between $H[f]$ and $Inf[f]$, which is a topic in cs.CG (Computational Geometry).
